                            <h1>
                            Jesus the Christ
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p2" class="">Elder Robert L. Backman</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p" class="">Of the Presidency of the Seventy</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">91911_000_005</span>
			<div class="figure">
				<img src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/gospel-library/magazine/ensignlp.nfo:o:246a.jpg" alt="Elder Robert L. Backman">
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p3" class="">While abridging the records of the Nephites, Mormon wrote, &ldquo;Behold, I am a disciple of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, the Son of God. I have been called of him to declare his word among his people, that they might have everlasting life.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/5.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 5:13</a>.) This humble yet straightforward declaration ought to express the feelings of all Latter-day Saints&mdash;disciples of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>, called to minister in his cause.</p>
			<div>
				<h2>Christ: More than a King</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p5" class="">Who is this Jesus whom we worship? Above all people on earth, we Latter-day Saints should appreciate the vital significance of Jesus of Nazareth&mdash;his role in the plan of salvation, his virgin birth, his immaculate life, his powerful teachings, his selfless death, his glorious <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2000/05/resurrection?lang=eng">resurrection</a>, his guidance of his Church.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p6" class="">In Lloyd Douglas&rsquo;s book, <span class="emphasis">The Robe,</span> is an imaginative account of the entry of Christ into Jerusalem, riding a donkey. Amid the hysteria of the excited multitude, ignorant of the significance of the event and of its chief Actor, occurs a conversation between two Greek slaves:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p7" class="">&ldquo;See him&mdash;close up?&rdquo; asked the uncouth Athenian.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p8" class="">Demetrius nodded &hellip; , turning away. &hellip;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p9" class="">&ldquo;Crazy?&rdquo; persisted the Athenian. &hellip;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p10" class="">&ldquo;No.&rdquo;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p11" class="">&ldquo;King?&rdquo;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p12" class="">&ldquo;No,&rdquo; muttered Demetrius &hellip; , &ldquo;not a king.&rdquo;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p13" class="">&ldquo;What is he then?&rdquo; &hellip;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p14" class="">&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; mumbled Demetrius &hellip; , &ldquo;but&mdash;he is something more important than a king.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">The Robe,</span> Boston: Houghton Mifflin Co., 1947, p. 74.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p15" class="">Jesus Christ is indeed more than a king; he is the Son of God, our Savior, our Redeemer, the author and finisher of our faith, King of kings, Lord of lords, Wonderful, Counselor, the Mighty God, the Everlasting Father, the Prince of Peace. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/12.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 12:2</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/rev/17.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Rev. 17:14</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/9.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 9:6</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p16" class="">That is what the gospel is all about. Without him, without his intervention in our behalf, we would be helpless in the face of Adam&rsquo;s transgression. We are indeed saved by grace &ldquo;through faith,&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/2.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 2:8</a>) or as Nephi wrote, &ldquo;It is by grace that we are saved, after all we can do&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/25.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 25:23</a>).</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p17" class="">&ldquo;All other things which pertain to our religion are only appendages&rdquo; to the testimony of Jesus&mdash;his death, burial, resurrection, and ascension into heaven. (<span class="emphasis">Teachings of the Prophet <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a>,</span> p. 121.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p18" class="">A little girl, misquoting the twenty-third Psalm, put everything in perspective. She said, &ldquo;The Lord is my shepherd. That&rsquo;s all I want!&rdquo; [see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/23.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 23:1</a>] What more could anyone want? What could be more desirable than to &ldquo;look unto [Jesus] in every thought&rdquo;? (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/6.36?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 6:36</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p19" class="">As we ponder our relationship to our Savior, may I paint some sketches of him that have helped me become acquainted with him and serve as standards by which I have tried to measure my life.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p20" class="">He was born of Mary&mdash;he had the power to die. He was the firstborn of the Father, the Son of God&mdash;he had the power to live and the capacity to live perfectly. We know that Jesus &ldquo;received not of the fulness at first, but continued from grace to grace, until he received a fulness.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/93.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 93:13</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p21" class="">As a youth the Lord &ldquo;increased in wisdom and stature, and in favour with God and man.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/2.52?lang=eng#51" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 2:52</a>.) During this growth process, he suffered &ldquo;temptations, and pain of body, hunger, thirst, and fatigue, even more than man can suffer.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:7</a>.) He experienced all of these things &ldquo;that his bowels may be filled with mercy, according to the flesh, that he may know according to the flesh how to succor his people according to their infirmities.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/7.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 7:12</a>.) There is nothing we experience&mdash;no heartache or joy&mdash;that he has not experienced more intensely; and his response to such experiences was perfect. He thus established a pattern for our own lives.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p22" class="">During his mortal life, Jesus gave us his gospel and organized his church. Jesus taught his disciples how to live more abundantly and showed us the way to happiness here and eternal life hereafter.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Miracles</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p24" class="">He performed many miracles. They were &ldquo;an important element in the work of Jesus Christ, being not only divine acts, but forming also a part of the divine teaching. &hellip; They were intended to be a proof to the Jews that Jesus was the Christ. &hellip; The miracles of healing also show how the law of love is to deal with the actual facts of life. Miracles were and are a response to faith, and its best encouragement.&rdquo; (<a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/topic/bible/">Bible</a> Dictionary, s.v. &ldquo;Miracles.&rdquo;)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p25" class="">Recall the pathos in one of Christ&rsquo;s greatest miracles, the raising of his friend Lazarus from the dead. The compassionate Savior responded to the pleas of his friends, but also delayed his coming in order to use the occasion to teach. &ldquo;I am glad for your sakes,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;that I was not there, to the intent ye may believe.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/11.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 11:15</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p26" class="">The mourning Martha said with childlike faith:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p27" class="">&ldquo;Lord, if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p28" class="">&ldquo;But I know, that even now, whatsoever thou wilt ask of God, God will give it thee.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p29" class="">&ldquo;Jesus saith unto her, Thy brother shall rise again.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p30" class="">&ldquo;Martha saith unto him, I know that he shall rise again in the resurrection at the last day.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p31" class="">&ldquo;Jesus said unto her, I am the resurrection, and the life: he that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/11.21-25?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 11:21&ndash;25</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p32" class="">Mary expressed similar feelings: &ldquo;If thou hadst been here, my brother had not died.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/11.32?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 11:32</a>.) And Jesus, seeing her and others weeping, &ldquo;groaned in the spirit, and was troubled,&rdquo; and he himself wept. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/11.33,35?lang=eng#32" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 11:33, 35</a>.) The depth of caring and compassion is remarkable and warmly inviting. Jesus, with the word of faith and power, said simply, &ldquo;Lazarus, come forth.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/11.43?lang=eng#42" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 11:43</a>.) And Lazarus did. A life restored and irrefutable evidence of Christ&rsquo;s divinity forever established as a basis of faith.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Disciple of the Living Christ</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p34" class="">I exult with Paul: &ldquo;O death, where is thy sting? O grave, where is thy victory?&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/15.55?lang=eng#54" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 15:55</a>.) Christ has won the victory. Death is conquered; life&mdash;eternal life&mdash;reigns triumphant. We are disciples of the living Christ. Though his body was laid in a borrowed sepulcher, he was resurrected on the third day, appearing to many.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p35" class="">Imagine yourself in the company of the disciples and other believers on the day of the Resurrection. Mere hours have passed since you witnessed the horrifying crucifixion of the gentle Nazarene. You have shared hopeless moments of profound sorrow; confused, knowing not where to turn, how to act. Your minds are clouded with mists of despair. Then two disciples join you with word that they have conversed with the Lord on the road to Emmaus. Dare you believe those who report, &ldquo;The Lord is risen indeed, and hath appeared to Simon&rdquo;? (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/24.34?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 24:34</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p36" class="">Luke recorded this remarkable event:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p37" class="">&ldquo;And as they thus spake, Jesus himself stood in the midst of them, and saith unto them, Peace be unto you.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p38" class="">&ldquo;But they were terrified and affrighted, and supposed that they had seen a spirit.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p39" class="">&ldquo;And he said unto them, Why are ye troubled? and why do thoughts arise in your hearts?</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p40" class="">&ldquo;Behold my hands and my feet, that it is I myself: handle me, and see; for a spirit hath not flesh and bones, as ye see me have.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p41" class="">&ldquo;And when he had thus spoken, he shewed them his hands and his feet.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/24.36-40?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 24:36&ndash;40</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p42" class="">That scene lives in my heart, for it heralds <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/immortality?lang=eng">immortality</a> for all of us. It assures us of continued life after death free from mortal pain and sorrow.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>His Atonement</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p44" class="">Jesus took upon himself the sins of all of us in Gethsemane and on the cross. He died that we might live. Who among us has not experienced the pain of sin? Who does not desperately need the balm of divine <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/general-conference/2005/10/forgiveness?lang=eng">forgiveness</a> to heal a wounded soul? Lehi taught his son, Jacob:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p45" class="">&ldquo;Wherefore, redemption cometh in and through the Holy Messiah; for he is full of grace and truth.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p46" class="">&ldquo;Behold he offereth himself a sacrifice for sin, to answer the ends of the law, unto all those who have a broken heart and a contrite spirit; and unto none else can the ends of the law be answered.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/2.6-7?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 2:6&ndash;7</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p47" class="">His was a &ldquo;great and last sacrifice,&rdquo; an &ldquo;infinite and eternal sacrifice,&rdquo; which none but the sinless Son of God could effect. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/34.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 34:10</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p48" class="">The way to eternal life has been cleared by the &ldquo;way, the truth, and the life.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/14.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 14:6</a>.) Why should we not accept the invitation to salvation as phrased by Peter, &ldquo;casting all your care upon him; for he careth for you.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/5.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 5:7</a>.)</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>His Commission</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p50" class="">&ldquo;Wherefore, how great the importance to make these things known unto the inhabitants of the earth.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/2.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 2:8</a>.) Jesus displayed a missionary zeal, a fervent desire that all the children of God enjoy the blessings of his gospel. Isn&rsquo;t it interesting that the last chapter of each of the Gospels contains an appeal from the risen Lord to spread the gospel.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p51" class="">On the wall of the main floor of the Church Office Building in Salt Lake City is a magnificent mural depicting Jesus Christ as a resurrected being standing among his eleven Apostles as he gives them a stirring charge to be missionaries to all the world:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p52" class="">&ldquo;Go ye therefore, and teach all nations, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/baptism?lang=eng">baptizing</a> them in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghost:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p53" class="">&ldquo;Teaching them to observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you: and, lo, I am with you alway, even unto the end of the world. Amen.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/28.19-20?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 28:19&ndash;20</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p54" class="">The Apostles who there stood with the Son of God responded to this call with faith, boldness, and power. We read that they were &ldquo;all filled with the Holy Ghost, and they spake the word of God with boldness.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/4.31?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 4:31</a>.) They had seen a resurrected being, had eaten with him, had felt his hands and feet. They knew, and knowing, they testified: &ldquo;For we cannot but speak the things which we have seen and heard.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/4.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 4:20</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p55" class="">Does that commission extend to us as his disciples? Perhaps we have not seen, in person, the risen Lord. But the testimony of his chosen witnesses is etched into our hearts by the Holy Spirit. We know, and knowing, we too must testify. Is there any question in the mind of any of us that this is one of the chief responsibilities we enjoy by reason of our membership in his Church? I began with Mormon&rsquo;s declaration, &ldquo;I have been called of him to declare his word among his people, that they might have everlasting life.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/5.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 5:13</a>.) Such is the calling of each of us.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Give Yourself to Christ</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p57" class="">What Christ desires from each of us is surrender, complete and total&mdash;a voluntary gift of trust, faith, and love. C. S. Lewis captured the spirit of this surrender:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p58" class="">&ldquo;Christ says, &lsquo;Give me All. I don&rsquo;t want so much of your time and so much of your money and so much of your work: I want You. I have not come to torment your natural self, but to kill it. No half-measures are any good. I don&rsquo;t want to cut off a branch here and a branch there, I want to have the whole tree down. &hellip; Hand over the whole natural self, all the desires which you think innocent as well as the ones you think wicked&mdash;the whole outfit. I will give you a new self instead. In fact, I will give you Myself: my own will shall become yours.&rsquo;&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Mere Christianity,</span> New York: Collier Books, 1960, p. 167.)</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>I Know That My Redeemer Lives</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p60" class="">As a disciple of Jesus Christ, the Son of God, I express my willingness to so submit myself to my Savior because I trust him, I believe him, and I love him. I say, with Job, &ldquo;I know that my redeemer liveth, and that he shall stand at the latter day upon the earth:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p61" class="">&ldquo;And though after my skin worms destroy this body, yet in my flesh shall I see God.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/job/19.25-26?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Job 19:25&ndash;26</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1991/11/jesus-the-christ.p62" class="">In the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
			</div>
		
                            
                            
                            
